Analysis of the mock Data

Florian Stijven

2024-04-12

1 Introduction

In this report, we analyze the mock data that resemble the data in the case study. These are data from a randomized trial in Alzheimers disease where the ADAS-Cog score has been evaluated at pre-determined measurement occasions. Additionally, baseline covariates are available; these will be adjusted for to increase efficiency.

We first read and explore the data. Next, we fit a mixed model for repeated measures (MMRM) and present the corresponding results. Finally, we use this fitted mixed model to estimate the treatment effect on the time scale with the meta time-component test (meta TCT) methodology.

2 Data Exploration

The Lighthouse data are read via the SAS data file. These data are in a partially long format because every post-randomization measurement has its own row, but the baseline measurement is represented by a column. For applying meta TCT, we need to fit a mixed model where the baseline measurement is also treated as a response instead of a baseline covariate. Hence, we reformat the data accordingly.

The baseline covariates and ADAS-Cog scores are summarized by treatment group in Table 2.1. By randomization, the distribution of baseline covariates should be identical across treatment groups, apart from discrepancies due to sampling variability.

3 Mixed Model for Repeated Measures

We now fit a MMRM where the vector of ADAS-Cog scores at baseline, 12, 24, 40, and 48 weeks is the response variable. The model is fitted with restricted maximum likelihood. We also add the following baseline covariates in the model:

  • SITE: This is a categorical variable for the study sites; we include a main effect for this variable.
  • AAPOEN: This is the APOE Allele status. We include an interaction between the measurement occasion and this variable.

In this model, we also assume that the mean ADAS-Cog scores at baseline are equal between both treatment groups. This holds by randomization. The mixed model is fitted with mmrm() from the mmrm R package.

We test for a treatment effect using the F-test with the Kenward-Rogers degrees of freedom approximation.

## Analysis of Fixed Effect Table (Type II F tests)
##             Num Df Denom Df F Statistic   Pr(>=F)    
## SITE            31   507.63       4.070 1.019e-11 ***
## AAPOEN           1   495.54       6.032   0.01439 *  
## Week             4   492.99      95.489 < 2.2e-16 ***
## Week:TRT         4   490.66       2.684   0.03090 *  
## AAPOEN:Week      4   490.73       2.484   0.04293 *  
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1

The p-value for the F-test is 0.031. There is thus is a significant treatment effect, but it is unclear how relevant this effect really is. A first step towards interpreting the magnitude of the treatment effect is to look at the estimated mean differences in ADAS-Cog scores.

Because we have included baseline covariates, we have to carefully define the treatment group-specific mean ADAS-Cog scores at the various measurement occasions. In what follows, we consider the estimated marginal means (EMMs, also known as least-squares means) where the factor levels of the center variable and the APOE variable receive weights proportional to their observed frequencies in the data. Alternatively, we could use equal weights for these factors, meaning that each center and APOE level receives the same weight. Which weights are most appropriate depends on whether these factors were controlled by the researchers and on the population one wishes to make inferences on.

The EMMs with proportional weights and the corresponding contrasts by measurement occasion are estimated with emmeans() and contrast() from the emmeans R package; the corresponding output is printed below. These contrasts indicate that the treatment effect increases with time. Still, it remains difficult to appreciate the relevance of the observed treatment effect, i.e., is a 2 points mean difference on the ADAS-Cog scale meaningful?

4 Meta Time-Component Test

In this section, we will use the EMMs from the previous section to estimate the treatment effect on the time scale. We use the meta TCT methodology as implemented in the TCT R package for this.

In the first step, we need to extract the EMMs at all treatment-measurement occasion combinations. We also need the corresponding covariance matrix. These quantities can be obtained from the emmGrid object that was returned by emmeans().

In the second step, we use TCT_meta() to estimate the measurement occasion-specific acceleration factors; the estimated acceleration factors are shown below. Note that the z-values for the estimated acceleration factors are equal to the corresponding t-values in the EMM contrasts. This is no coincidence and always holds for the "score" tests for the time-specific acceleration factors. The p-values below and the p-values for the EMM contrasts differ slightly because TCT_meta() uses the standard normal distribution instead of the t-distribution to compute the p-value.

## Meta-Time Component Test: 
## 
## Coefficients: 
##   Estimate Std. Error z value  p value                  CI
## 1  0.50813   0.277135 -1.7894 0.073545 (0.013338, 1.03995)
## 2  0.78298   0.100656 -1.9427 0.052054 (0.580660, 1.00226)
## 3  0.78183   0.117791 -1.9339 0.053131 (0.585447, 1.00239)
## 4  0.75326   0.098311 -3.1796 0.001475 (0.559459, 0.91105)
## alpha = 0.05
## 
## Interpolation Method: spline
## Estimation and Inference: score

The estimated measurement occasion-specific acceleration factors do not contradict the assumption of proportional slowing, i.e., the assumption that the acceleration factor is constant over time. Indeed, the estimates are all within one standard error of 0.50. Therefore, we can proceed to estimating the common acceleration factor.

The object returned by TCT_meta() can be used as argument to TCT_meta_common() to estimate the common acceleration factor. We use two estimation methods: (i) the score estimator with adaptively selected weights and (ii) the least-squares estimator.

These two estimators lead to very similar results. The estimated common acceleration factor is about 0.77 or 0.80. The estimated treatment effect corresponds to slowing disease progression with about 20% a very relevant effect. The p-values and confidence intervals vary a bit more between these estimators and also depend on whether the parametric bootstrap is used. Since the sample size is relatively small, the parametric bootstrap should be preferred. Indeed, simulations revealed that inference based on the parametric bootstrap is closer to nominal in small sample sizes.

5 Conclusion

Using the classic analysis method, the MMRM and the F-test, we found a significant treatment effect, p = 0.031. Based on contrasts in EMMs, the estimated treatment effects on the ADAS-Cog scale at 40 and 48 weeks are a mean difference of -1.13 and -2.06 points, respectively. The relevance of these treatment effects is unclear. The estimated common acceleration factor is 0.8, p = 0.018 (using the least-squares estimator and parametric bootstrap). The meta TCT approach thus reveals a clinically modest effect.The corresponding 95 % CI is (0.65, 0.94), which reveals that clinically large treatment effects e.g., slowing of more than 50 % can be excluded. In addition, the p-value is modestly smaller as compared to F-test in the MMRM.
